      "writtenOn": "2026-05-13T02:06:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks for your review and catching the resource retention issue.\n \nAddressed in the latest patchset, but with clear() + shrink_to_fit() rather than\nerase(). Erasing the map entry from writeFruCache() is unsafe because that function runs inside sdbusplus::Timer::timeoutHandler() (see sdbusplus/include/sdbusplus/timer.hpp). After invoking userCallBack(), timeoutHandler() continues to access eventSource:\n\n    if (userCallBack)\n    {\n        userCallBack();   // \u003c- our writeFruCache() runs here\n    }\n\n    int running;\n    if (sd_event_source_get_enabled(eventSource, \u0026running) \u003c 0 ||\n        running \u003d\u003d SD_EVENT_ONESHOT)\n    {\n        stop();           // \u003c- also touches eventSource\n    }\n\nErasing the map entry inside the callback would destroy the Timer mid-dispatch, freeing eventSource while the dispatcher is still using it — a Use-After-Free.\n\nCompromise: Added releaseWriteCtx() helper that does clear() + shrink_to_fit() \non the data buffer, releasing the dominant memory cost but keeping the Timer\nobject.\n\nOn unbounded growth: the map is keyed by uint8_t fruDeviceId, and after fixing the validation order, entries are only inserted for IDs that exist in deviceHashes. Map size is therefore bounded by the platform\u0027s FRU topology, not unbounded.",
      "parentUuid": "c5a965f2_2e35b1e7",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 161,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 161,
        "endChar": 24
      },
      "revId": "ac434dd7bc59eee2bd4078966825df5ed969d751",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
